  "prompt": "What can cause astigmatism?",
  "response": "Astigmatism is a common eye condition that can cause blurred or distorted vision. It occurs when the cornea or lens of the eye is irregularly shaped, leading to an inability to focus light properly onto the retina. There are several factors that can contribute to the development of astigmatism:\n\n1. **Genetics**: Astigmatism often runs in families, suggesting a genetic component. If one or both parents have astigmatism, there is a higher likelihood that their children will develop it as well.\n\n2. **Irregular Corneal Shape**: The cornea is the clear front surface of the eye. In a normal eye, the cornea has a smooth, round shape. In astigmatism, the cornea is often shaped more like a football or an egg, causing light to focus on multiple points rather than a single point on the retina.\n\n3. **Irregular Lens Shape**: Similar to the cornea, the lens inside the eye can also have an irregular shape, leading to astigmatism. This is less common than corneal astigmatism.\n\n4. **Eye Surgery**: Certain types of eye surgery, such as cataract surgery, can sometimes cause or worsen astigmatism. This can occur if the surgical incisions affect the shape of the cornea.\n\n5. **Eye Injuries**: Trauma to the eye can alter the shape of the cornea or lens, leading to astigmatism.\n\n6. **Keratoconus**: This is a progressive eye disease in which the cornea thins and bulges into a cone-like shape. Keratoconus can cause astigmatism due to the irregular shape of the cornea.\n\nWhile astigmatism can be present from birth, it can also develop or change over time. Regular eye exams are important to monitor and manage this condition effectively.",
